        <name>22.3.1.3 Diagonalisable 3x3 task</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The matrix \(A = {@a@}\) has eigenvalues \({@eigenvalues[1][1]@},{@eigenvalues[1][2]@},{@eigenvalues[1][3]@}\). The eigenvector corresponding to the eigenvalue \({@eigenvalues[1][1]@}\) is \(X={@col(slmat,1)@}\) or any multiple.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Investigate the eigenvectors associated to the repeated eigenvalue \({@eigenvalues[1][3]@}\).&lt;br&gt;
Enter linearly independent eigenvectors as &lt;i&gt;columns&lt;/i&gt; into the following matrix.&lt;br&gt;If there are less than two linearly independent eigenvectors, fill the rest of the columns by zeroes: &lt;div&gt;[[input:anseigenvectors]] [[validation:anseigenvectors]].&amp;nbsp;[[feedback:eigenvectors]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Can \(A\) be diagonalized? [[input:ansdiagonalisable]] [[validation:ansdiagonalisable]]&amp;nbsp;[[feedback:diagonalisability]]&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;We must solve \(AY = {@eigenvalues[1][3]@}Y\) for the required eigenvector, i.e. \[{@a@}{@pcovect(vars)@} = {@pcovect(eigenvalues[1][3]*vars)@}.\] Each equation simplifies to \({@eve_equ@}\). We have just one equation in three unknowns, so we can
            choose &lt;strong&gt;two&lt;/strong&gt; values arbitrarily. For example (choosing some variables to be zero) we find solutions \({@vars[1]@}={@evs[1][1]@}\), \({@vars[2]@}={@evs[1][2]@}\) and \({@vars[3]@}={@evs[1][3]@}\); and \({@vars[1]@}={@evs[2][1]@}\),
            \({@vars[2]@}={@evs[2][2]@}\) and \({@vars[3]@}={@evs[2][3]@}\). These give rise to linearly independent eigenvectors \[ Y_1 = {@col(eigenvectors,1)@}, \quad Y_2 = {@col(eigenvectors,2)@}.\]
        &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;We can thus form a non-singular modal matrix \(P\) from \(Y_1\) and \(Y_2\) together with \(X\) (given): \[P = {@modal@}.\] We can then indeed diagonalize \(A\) through the transformation \[P^{-1}AP = D = {@diagmat@}.\]
        &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
